1
00:00:01,120 --> 00:00:02,920
- Service Level Management.

2
00:00:02,920 --> 00:00:05,550
This is another one you
need to know in-depth.

3
00:00:05,550 --> 00:00:07,540
First, let's start with the purpose.

4
00:00:07,540 --> 00:00:09,330
The purpose of the
service level management

5
00:00:09,330 --> 00:00:12,180
practice is to set clear
business-based targets

6
00:00:12,180 --> 00:00:14,370
for service performance
so that the delivery

7
00:00:14,370 --> 00:00:15,976
of a service can be properly assessed,

8
00:00:15,976 --> 00:00:18,675
monitored, and managed
against these targets.

9
00:00:18,675 --> 00:00:21,100
It's going to provide us
with end to end visibility

10
00:00:21,100 --> 00:00:22,770
of the organization's services.

11
00:00:22,770 --> 00:00:24,110
It's going to do this by establishing

12
00:00:24,110 --> 00:00:25,770
a shared view of the services and the

13
00:00:25,770 --> 00:00:27,860
target service levels with the customers,

14
00:00:27,860 --> 00:00:30,692
so both the customers and
us know what to expect.

15
00:00:30,692 --> 00:00:32,730
We're also going to focus on collecting,

16
00:00:32,730 --> 00:00:35,340
analyzing, storing, and
reporting the relevant

17
00:00:35,340 --> 00:00:37,020
metrics to ensure that we're meeting

18
00:00:37,020 --> 00:00:38,490
the service levels.

19
00:00:38,490 --> 00:00:39,760
We also want to make sure
that we're performing

20
00:00:39,760 --> 00:00:41,580
service level reviews, to ensure the

21
00:00:41,580 --> 00:00:43,080
current services continue to meet

22
00:00:43,080 --> 00:00:45,495
the organization and the customer's needs.

23
00:00:45,495 --> 00:00:47,090
We also are going to make sure that we're

24
00:00:47,090 --> 00:00:48,980
capturing and reporting service issues

25
00:00:48,980 --> 00:00:50,330
including performance against our

26
00:00:50,330 --> 00:00:52,050
defined service levels.

27
00:00:52,050 --> 00:00:56,090
So, if I said I want
to have 99.999% uptime,

28
00:00:56,090 --> 00:00:57,870
service level management
is going to measure

29
00:00:57,870 --> 00:01:01,035
my performance and see if
I'm meeting that level.

30
00:01:01,035 --> 00:01:03,050
Now, all of these service levels

31
00:01:03,050 --> 00:01:04,670
are going to be written
down in what's known

32
00:01:04,670 --> 00:01:07,302
as an SLA, or a Service Level Agreement.

33
00:01:07,302 --> 00:01:09,880
A Service Level Agreement is a documented

34
00:01:09,880 --> 00:01:11,500
agreement between a service provider

35
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:13,490
and a customer that identifies services

36
00:01:13,490 --> 00:01:16,140
required and the expected
level of service.

37
00:01:16,140 --> 00:01:18,920
This is going to tell you
what metrics you need to meet.

38
00:01:18,920 --> 00:01:20,970
The SLA is a tool that's used to measure

39
00:01:20,970 --> 00:01:22,590
the performance of services from

40
00:01:22,590 --> 00:01:23,805
the customer's point of view.

41
00:01:23,805 --> 00:01:25,490
Now, there's a couple of things you need

42
00:01:25,490 --> 00:01:26,900
to do to make sure that
you're going to have

43
00:01:26,900 --> 00:01:28,710
a successful SLA.

44
00:01:28,710 --> 00:01:30,270
First, you want to make sure it's

45
00:01:30,270 --> 00:01:31,900
related to a defined service.

46
00:01:31,900 --> 00:01:33,600
It can't be something generalized,

47
00:01:33,600 --> 00:01:35,660
like customer is happy.

48
00:01:35,660 --> 00:01:37,320
What is the customer happy with?

49
00:01:37,320 --> 00:01:39,640
They're happy with the
email service delivery.

50
00:01:39,640 --> 00:01:43,000
They want it to be fast, what
does fast really mean, right?

51
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:44,880
You need to make sure
you're defining the outcome

52
00:01:44,880 --> 00:01:47,400
you want, not just operational metrics.

53
00:01:47,400 --> 00:01:49,297
So, if the customer says "I want the

54
00:01:49,297 --> 00:01:52,050
"email to be fast" well, does that mean

55
00:01:52,050 --> 00:01:53,470
if I get it there in five seconds

56
00:01:53,470 --> 00:01:55,250
they're happy, or if I get there in

57
00:01:55,250 --> 00:01:56,650
five minutes they're happy?

58
00:01:56,650 --> 00:01:58,180
I need to be able to define, really

59
00:01:58,180 --> 00:01:59,830
what does fast mean?

60
00:01:59,830 --> 00:02:01,010
And I don't want to just do that from

61
00:02:01,010 --> 00:02:02,900
an output perspective, but also from an

62
00:02:02,900 --> 00:02:04,231
outcome perspective.

63
00:02:04,231 --> 00:02:06,310
Also, we want to make sure our agreement

64
00:02:06,310 --> 00:02:07,500
is between the service provider

65
00:02:07,500 --> 00:02:09,060
and the service consumer, and it

66
00:02:09,060 --> 00:02:11,510
reflects their opinions accurately.

67
00:02:11,510 --> 00:02:13,022
Because if the customer says

68
00:02:13,022 --> 00:02:15,150
"The email service should be fast"

69
00:02:15,150 --> 00:02:16,532
and they say five minutes is fast,

70
00:02:16,532 --> 00:02:19,290
but the customer, or the
consumer in this case,

71
00:02:19,290 --> 00:02:20,770
would think that it needs to be fast

72
00:02:20,770 --> 00:02:23,470
meaning five seconds,
there's a disconnect there.

73
00:02:23,470 --> 00:02:25,290
So we want to make sure
we understand it both

74
00:02:25,290 --> 00:02:27,560
from the customer's
perspective, in our contract

75
00:02:27,560 --> 00:02:29,640
but also from our consumer's perspective,

76
00:02:29,640 --> 00:02:31,005
because that's really what the SLA

77
00:02:31,005 --> 00:02:33,684
should be focused on, is
that server's consumer.

78
00:02:33,684 --> 00:02:36,160
And the final key to writing a good SLA

79
00:02:36,160 --> 00:02:37,961
is making sure you write it simply.

80
00:02:37,961 --> 00:02:40,870
Make sure that it's easy to
understand by all parties.

81
00:02:40,870 --> 00:02:42,630
This isn't a contract, it doesn't need

82
00:02:42,630 --> 00:02:44,570
to be written with legal jargon.

83
00:02:44,570 --> 00:02:46,460
Instead, make it simple and easy,

84
00:02:46,460 --> 00:02:47,660
so that anyone who picks it up

85
00:02:47,660 --> 00:02:49,054
can understand what you're talking about.

86
00:02:49,054 --> 00:02:50,825
When you're writing your SLAs,

87
00:02:50,825 --> 00:02:52,540
you always want to be focused on the

88
00:02:52,540 --> 00:02:53,940
different relationships.

89
00:02:53,940 --> 00:02:56,090
That includes things like
relationship management,

90
00:02:56,090 --> 00:02:57,780
your supplier management, the different

91
00:02:57,780 --> 00:03:00,280
skills and competencies,
the business liaisons,

92
00:03:00,280 --> 00:03:01,800
and the business analysts.

93
00:03:01,800 --> 00:03:03,110
All of that is things that are going to

94
00:03:03,110 --> 00:03:05,110
feed into this SLA, and making sure

95
00:03:05,110 --> 00:03:07,080
we understand who's responsible for what,

96
00:03:07,080 --> 00:03:08,620
and to what level.

97
00:03:08,620 --> 00:03:10,430
Now, our service level management

98
00:03:10,430 --> 00:03:13,390
is built around these
various information sources.

99
00:03:13,390 --> 00:03:14,980
One of those is our SLA, right,

100
00:03:14,980 --> 00:03:16,280
that's the customer engagement

101
